ading `org.graal`, but it may not be necessary. I wonder if it’s having trouble with `javax.crypto`, which the platform might include. The Platform classloader loads `java.*` but not the classpath. \\n\\nWhen loading classes that aren't part of `org.bouncycastle`, it uses the Platform classloader. Since Bouncy Castle references `javax.crypto`, that could be a factor. But why is there still no coverage? I need to keep digging into this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class order in tests**\\n\\nI’m trying to understand why ClassOrderer didn't prioritize NativeLoaderTest before FipsStatusTest in the native image. JUnit platform uses @Order annotations, where NativeLoaderTest is set to @Order(0). However, FipsStatusTest runs with @BeforeAll, which makes me wonder if that’s impacting the execution order. If FipsStatus is ready, it might skip loading drivers. It seems we might need to use a public API to start a separate JVM process for certain tests.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering reflection and APIs**\\n\\nI’m reflecting on how reflection is generally prohibited unless it’s through a public API. I wonder if MethodHandles could be an option since they involve reflection too. The FipsNative class in the org.bouncycastle.crypto.fips package is public and has methods like getServices, isEnabled, and setEnabled, but it doesn’t seem to call loadDriver. I need to better understand dynamic-access tracking coverage, as it might only apply to Java tests with an agent.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Java Initialization Issues**\\n\\nI’m looking into whether global runtime arguments in Java might interfere with my tests after the `@BeforeAll` annotation. I think they shouldn't be causing issues, but maybe build arguments like `-D java` could be initializing `NativeLoader` at build time. I wonder if `NativeLoader` gets initialized during this process when selected. Its static fields don't seem to read properties, yet `FipsStatus` could be related to runtime conditions. It's a bit confusing!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Understanding JUnit ClassOrderer**\\n\\nI'm exploring the JUnit ClassOrderer and its OrderAnnotation. It seems that when classes are marked with @Order, they're sorted by their assigned value. The default order value is Integer.MAX_VALUE/2, which is interesting. For example, NativeLoaderTest has a value of 0, FipsStatusTest is set at 1, and ClassUtil doesn’t specify an order. I want to make sure I'm correctly grasping how this impacts the testing sequence.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ogfQplhx8q121Jt6CtZv1kLS|fc_0674e00c56c31857016a3f7954e3088197bbda2502a84a0d6b", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge3/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.bouncycastle/bc-fips/2.1.2/main/extracted/org/bouncycastle/util/DumpInfo.java", "offset": 1, "limit": 180}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 10200, "output": 2247, "cacheRead": 61952, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 74399, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782544688995, "responseId": "resp_0674e00c56c31857016a3f79322b208197b6323c853aefef22"}}
